    'from' => 'gsw@aloft.att.com',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ad733',
    'body' => 'On Wednesday, June 05, David J. Golden wrote:
>         I\'m not sure how *reducing* the amount of energy to reach a certain
> speed takes the kinetic energy weapon away ... if you cut the energy to
> reach speed A from Energy to 0.25Energy, that just means that if I still
> spend Energy I now get up to 2*A! So the ship becomes an even *more*
> powerful weapon.

That is precisely the problem with the previously "official" version
of thruster plates--they gave you free kinetic energy. "Realistic"
reaction drives don\'t solve the problem, since you still have ships
travelling at very high speeds and now every ship has a very powerful
fusion gun in back.

The problem is that you want ships to be capable of high acceleration
and speeds. This is the only way to make maneuver drives a feasible
alternative for in-system travel, among other things.

The solution is to state that these very fast-moving ships really
don\'t have the tremendous amounts of kinetic energy that they should
have. Suppose a maneuver drive also included a field generator that
affected the "apparent mass" of the ship. With the generator on, you
can accelerate quickly and to very high speeds. Turn the generator
off, and the ship drops down to a much lower speed (thrusters only?).

I realize there are some issues to be resolved if you want a more
thorough explanation, but they are not insurmountable. The biggest
issue probably is how the theory of relativity plays in. Possible
answers:
 o it doesn\'t (it\'s a "magic" type of field anyway)--the effects of
   relativity are as if the field were off
 o this results in extra energy being expended/lost (a cost to run
   the M-drive, especially at high speeds/accelerations)
 o this limits your maximum attainable speed (say, to below 0.1c)
   and puts stress on the ship/drives

Someone else asked:
> 2. Is there a logical technical reason that Traveller does not use 
> FTL travel akin to Trek\'s Warp Drive where one goes through normal space
> with a jump bubble around the ship. What about FTL communication, is there a
> logical technical reason why Traveller does not have FTL communication? 

Because that is not the way the Traveller universe works. With jumps
taking a week at a time and no faster method of communication, the
universe is more diverse and generally a more exciting place to be.
You could invent such things, but they would change the nature of the
campaign.

