> So thrustes don\'t change the momentum of the ship.  When you turn off
> the drive, you stop moving?

My main point is that a solution is needed for consistency in the
universe, a place in which many people have starships but planets
are not regularly being destroyed, orbiting space stations are
common, etc.

However, the concept I had in mind was more along the lines of this:

The "zeta field" (or whatever) allows you to achieve higher speeds by
changing your "apparent mass". A maneuver drive also has thrusters,
which would change your momentum (and kinetic energy) whether or not
the field is active. However, your "speed" would be higher if the
field is on. Fusion rockets could still exist, but would be at quite
a disadvantage and likely considered a threat to shipping lanes,
planets, etc. Note that the "zeta field" does not need be compatible
with fusion rockets, so you don\'t automatically get a supership by
strapping one onto an old fusion "torch-ship".

This explanation should be good enough for most people, I think.
There are certainly some issues with relativity (which also affects
"apparent mass") as well as whether (and how) to preserve momentum,
kinetic energy, or both when you turn the field on/off, but these
are not insurmountable problems.

