    'from' => 'FKiesche3@aol.com',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ad790',
    'topic' => 'Why Johnny Wont Compute',
    'body' => 'Greetings All:

Im (still) in the midst of preparing for a new Traveller campaign (Im
leaning towards the Classic setting, but might hold off until the first T4
items come out to see if well switch there). Ive been going through things
that look odd since the original incarnation of Traveller to todays
technology. Of course, one of the biggest glaring differences are in the way
Traveller portrayed computers vs. what we have today (and this difference
is, as we all know, one of the longest sources of debate starting from the
Origins seminars I attended way back when to todays discussions on how T4
will look!).

Ive thought of a few things to present to my players and would like to run
them past you and your collective wisdom.

Reason One for difference: Traveller was written in the mid-1970s. We
werent wired then they way we are now and nobody really thought wed advance
as quickly. So it has a sort of clunky anachronistic charm. I feel
uncomfortable changing the rules because its like picking at a loose thread
on your suit: You might end up unraveling the whole thing.

Reason Two for difference: Most of the ships in the Traveller universe are
built for rough travel. Its a jungle out there: Unfriendly powers, pirates,
troublesome natives. You never know when youre going to run into a storm
while re-fueling around a gas giant, or a bubble in hyperspace. The computers
are built military style--ultra-rough and tough to take a lot of punishment.

Reason Three for difference: Many years ago, humaniti had much better
computers. Heck, they even developed computers that would think for
themselves and had psionic powers! Then some of these telepathic AIs tried
to take things over. That was the start of the Psionic Suppressions--and of
