I think the exposion of skills in Traveller is causing a loss of comman
sense.  \'Fencing\' skill is a great example.  If you have property to sell
you find a buyer.  Why do you need a special skill just because the property
has been pinched??  I suppose you could claim the skill allows the seller a
chance to know the buyer is realy working for the police, but simply being
an alert player would work as well and lead the player to beleive that his
presense during the game matters!  Otherwise every action the players make
is now dictated by a simple role of the dice.  No need for the players to
put any thought into their action just role a few dice and see if you succeed.

Another example is Gunsmith.  (Yes I do know that being a gunsmith requires
special training) But mechanical skill already covers this.  And with so
many types of \'guns\' in Traveller you now have to break it down into \'Rifle
GunSmith\', \'Body Pistol GunSmith\', \'Laser Carbine GunSmith\', \'Gauss Rifle
GunSmith\' and on and on.

In GT there were only six basic stats.  Each was important in it\'s own
right.  In the same way a small subset of skills makes each skill important
and meaningful.



