Ok, I see where you\'re going..so now days we don\'t allow
computers to become powerful enough to challenge bio-superiority.
 
How about I give you a technical reason that keeps the big, clunky,
power hungry computers?

Reason Four:  Gravtics!  The development of gravity control technology
had a very un-welcome side-effect, it played regular *hell* with
microelectronics.  In the presence of a working anti-grav device
anything more delicate than a vacuum tube burns right out.  In fact, I
work it such that a landing anti-grav ship can take out half the
planet\'s electronics...if it\'s all chip and transistor based.

- ----
Imperial Encyclopedia:

Some cultures never discovered gravity control and persisted with
electronics development.  This led to them inventing things that would
make our electronic devices look like bundles of sticks. OTOH, without
the advances coming from gravtics research, these misguided societies
are invariably limited to their own worlds, and begin to stagnate and
slide into overpopulation, wars, and eventually world wide
catastrophes!  [Imperial propaganda.  <g>]

Our scouts have come across several of these worlds.  In many cases,
we find destroyed societies with the populance reduced to barbarism.  

Occasionally, we find them in time to help them reverse their
technological direction and travel down the correct path of
development.  Until these worlds can retool their technologies they
are declared as travel restricted zones.

Most worlds discovered and began developing technologies based on
gravtics.  The ability to control gravity is one of the foundations of
our technology.  It has made our star spanning culture possible. 
Loosing some miniaturization in electronics is a small price to pay.
- ----

This gives us big, clunky, power hungry computers (and other
electronics), but as a trade off we get gravity control, T-Plates,
Jump Drives and Fusion in a can!

Eris
