=> increase in scope and complexity. That\'s why in colonial societies, the
=> artisans and craftsmen are the ones who build the society. This is
=> based on their ability to fabricate and repair stuff from over there.

I agree.  However, I also believe that a plateau will be reached when humanity
can no longer learn enough to repair high tech equipment _without_ specific high
tech repair tools & equipment (eg: silicon chip design, for example).  I see
this type of stuff in the automotive trade all the time.  Believe me, no
mechanic I know of could repair any of the sensors or actuators on some of
today\'s cars, not to mention a burned out ECM (ie: computer). They\'re too
miniturized, for one thing.  When things are designed to be resiliant, they are
often equally difficult to repair ("replacement" is usually pretty easy,
though).  As things become more and more sophisticated, I would imagine that the
components would become equally integrated until one epoxy-sealed black box did
everything.  There will always be widgets and thingies, however  8-)

I have seen a hard drive that belonged to a customer a few years ago.  It seems
that he had a hard disk failure and was so mad that he fired off three rounds
from his .357 Magnum into his hard drive.  Now this would be a good example of
battle damage and NO amount of tinkering and fiddling would bring that drive
back from the dead (even *one* round would have put it out of commission).
 
=> Personal military goods are a prime example of this. In WWII, the
=> ability of American GI\'s to tinker with other nation\'s weapons and
=> equipment and make them go was noted often by historians (reference
=> check any one?). This is in the absence of the logistic train that
=> supports the other product.

I remember Avalon Hill\'s "Squad Leader" taking this into account as well  8-)
 
=> IMO, a variety of skills is necessary, if the guidance is there for
=> acquiring them.

Living long enough to learn all of these skills then becomes an issue 8-)

As technology advances, however, a single skill point in "Electronics" becomes
far more valuable than a single skill point in "Climbing".  If electronics is
going to become such a popular/necessary skill in the future, it should be
broken down into a number of cascade skills to allow for better roleplaying as
an electronics specialist.
