    'topic' => ' Foundations of Traveller',
    'body' => 'At 05:19 PM 6/7/96 +0100, you wrote:
>
>
>>But there is another, less obvious, reminder of the Ancients. At some time in
>>their travels, the Ancients visited Earth and carried away several thousand
>>near-intelligent cavemen. 
>
>If this happened c 300,000BC then the "near-intelligent cavemen" cannot have
>been Homo sapiens, but some earlier human type. The small gene-pool of
>abducted "cavemen" have therefore undergone 300,000 years of divergent
>evolution from the base population on Terra.  The Terran population evolved
>into Homo Sapiens, but the transported populations would not have done so -
>they would have evolved into other geni(?) of Homo or into entirely new
>species: some of these transported populations may never have evolved full
>intelligence.  This means that neither the Vilani or the Zhodani can
>possibly be Homo Sapiens and must belong to some other human genus.
>
>I don\'t know if this is the intended consequence of the Ancient Abduction,
>but its a fascinating idea!

Actually it was originally beleived that the Genus Homo Sapiens was only in
the order of 20-50,000 years old based on fossil evidence obtained from a
number of sites in west africa.  This was held to be absolutely true for
nearly thirty years.  However, over the least decade a number of sites have
begun turning up, particularly in the southern african fossil beds that
would seem to push the origin of Homo Sapiens back to the 150-200,000 year
time frame.  What this means is that Homo Sapiens exited contemperainous
with several other genus for thousands of years.

In theory the Ancients would have had at least three different Homo speicies
to work with.

Derek Stanley

