>Only 1 thing about it.  Although it doesn\'t bother me a bit, there 
>are a few people of deeper faith who might find bringing 
>Religious/Theologian matters into a role-playing game a little 
>offensive.  In my games, alien philosophies and religions are at 
>times part of the backdrop.  Others may not be quite so open-minded 
>on the subject of religion though.

The truely difficult part is one of treating religious beleifs with respect
(which I imagine you do) -- especially the ones which are not your own!  I
generally include in my own campaigns the assumption that most major human
religions will continue well into the future, but that they are not high on
the list of the priorities of most adventurers.  I have had players wish to
specify reigion as part of their character -- in those cases I simply insist
that they include the practice in their roleplaying as well.

Best added as a GM\'s option, though.  It\'s way too easy to turn religious
NPC\'s in to jokes.  Many published adventures seemed to be of the "wackey
sect of the day" sort, and I found them a bit annoying.  Roleplaying a
missionary, with the right GM, could be very interesting, though.
