    'body' => '(Continued from previous message)

 to detectives, and to non-police citizens.  I ask weird questions
 like this.)

 ::>Bribery (D)

 Default?  Hell, no!  It\'s _real_ easy to muff a bribe attempt -
 that\'s how most bribery arrests are made!

 ::>Fast Talk (D) [Refers to convincing someone to do/think something by
 ::>spurious logic and/or intellectual intimidation.]

 Persuasion.  Covers it, plus "legitimate" discourse as well.

 ::>Forensics

 ::>Gambling (D)

 Default only if it includes _playing_, but not _organizing/operating_.
 If it refers to running illicit games, not default.

 ::>(Intrusion has been replaced by Break and Enter and Pickpocket)

 No, keep Intrusion and Pickpocket.  See above.

 ::>(Investigation has been removed.  In my opinion it is a combination of
 ::>Forensics, Interrogation, Perception, and Streetwise.)

 On that basis, BlackMarket could be covered by Trader/Broker and
 Streetwise.  Certainly, police-type investigations encompass all
 of these - but there\'s an element of organizing the knowledge
 gained from all of those sources which just isn\'t implied by the
 combo.  Keep Investigation.


 ::>***TECHNICAL SKILLS*********************

 ::>Animal Rider (C)  [note, this is here because technically, it\'s a vehicle]
 ::> -Uniped  : giant snakes, snails, etc.
 ::> -Biped : Ton Tons and similar beasties.
 ::> -Multiped : horses, hivers (who\'s driving who? :-)
 ::> [Should one have to choose a specific animal instead?]
 ::> [Again, I really don\'t think this skill should be default.]

 At low tech levels and low population densities, it probably
 should be.  I\'d also include Animal-drawn wheeled vehicle in this
 group.

 ::>Animal Care (C)  [includes training, maintaining, packing, and husbandry]
 ::> -Choose specific animal.

 ::>Aircraft (G)
 ::> -Helicopter : copters, autogyros.
 ::> -Prop Plane : including VTOL at TL-7+.
 ::> -Jet Plane : including VTOL and trans-atmosphere at TL-8+.
 ::> -Light-t-Air : blimps, baloons.
 ::> -Glider :
 ::> -Jet Pack :
 ::>[Can anyone think of others?  Are the last two too specific? I was
 ::>thinking of lumping them into "Personal Flyer" or something like that.]

 From knowing several people who fly (as pilots), I\'d be inclined
 to advise you to substitute "Fixed-Wing Single-Engine" and
 "Fixed-Wing Multiple-Engine" for "Prop" and "Jet".  Especially
 since at the high-end Cessna/Piper, you\'re getting a lot of
 overlap in both technique and performance with low-end Lear.

 ::>Communications (DM) (DH)

 Is this "using a telephone/walkie-talkie" or "using a ham radio
 setup"?  If the latter, not a default.  It\'s also possible that
 we\'re talking "communication" as a set of techniques for effective
 delivery of information, regardless of method, in which case it
 becomes a "science" or a "scholar", and not a default.

 ::>Computer (C)
 ::> -Programming
 ::> -Repair
 ::> -Hacking
 ::> -Applications (DH)

 If by "hacking" you mean breaking into computers, no.  That\'s
 called "cracking" or "being a vandal".  Unless you\'re being
 paid to do it to test the computer security of the company that\'s
 paying you, in which case it\'s "tiger teaming", a specific
 activity that true hackers can engage in with no loss of face.
 Any other legitimate meaning of "hacking" in connection with
 computers is strictly covered by programming - and even crackers
 have to have some knowledge of programming.  For that task, go
 with Programming skill, DM+Intrusion skill or some fraction
 thereof.

 I harp on the distinction between "hacking" and "cracking"
 because (a) many "hackers" (my sense) get offended when you lump
 "crackers" in with us, and (b) there\'s a non-trivial amount of
 overlap between the hacker (both senses) community and the RPG
 community.  Crackers frequently call themselves "hackers" to try
 to share in the true glory of the name, which some of them might
 even understand; all they succeed in doing is contaminating the
 name in the eyes of the public.

 ::>Designer (G)
 ::> -Spacecraft :

 Space/Star craft (nit).

 ::> -Architectural :
 ::> -Vehicular :
 ::>[Can anyone think of others?  This is supposed to be "engineering" in the
 ::>20th century sense, but is called "design" to distinguish it.]

 Computer.  While a computer designer must be able to program, not
 every programmer can design a computer - not even a virtual
 machine.  Allow Computer Design skill for tasks that require
 programming skill, but not \\vice-versa\\.

 ::>Farming

 Group:  Dirt and Hydroponic.

 ::>Grav Craft (C)
 ::> -Personal Flyer: grav belt, grav cycle.
 ::> -Grav Vehicle (DH): air rafts of various sorts, including
 ::>spacecraft when using antigrav.

 - Belt
 - Cycle
 - Air Raft (atmo limit)
 - G-Carrier (out-of-atmo)
 - Shuttle (includes docking with orbiting stations/craft)
 - SpaceShip (when using grav)

 ::>Prospecting [Or is this just a combination of Sensor Ops and Geology?]

 No, keep separate.  Sensor Ops may not tell you everything you
 need to know.  You may also need tools and techniques not
 available to the planetographer.  This would be a skill that a
 "Belter" has - and "Belter" is an occupation, not a skill.

 ::> Space (G)
 ::> -Pilot
 ::> -Navigation
 ::> -Engineer
 ::> -Gunnery
 ::> -Vacc
 ::>[Am I missing any here?]

 Zero-G skills.



 ::>***PROFESSIONAL SKILLS********************

 ::>Diplomacy (D)

 Not a chance.  Some people never learn to be even ordinarily
 "diplomatic".

 ::>Law

 ::>Medicine (DM) (DH) [I like the idea of Med-1 being 1st Aid up to Med-4
 ::>being surgeon].

 No, not a default.  Only a minority ever learn even First Aid
 beyond "I got an owie.  Lemme put an adhesive bandage on it".


 ::>***MERCANTILE SKILLS************************
 ::>[I\'d like formal definitions of the skills below, I\'m not sure what they
 ::>refer to specifically]

 ::>Administration

 Probably should be a "Professional" skill; it\'s needed even in
 non-mercantile contexts.  I read it as being the ability to manage
 an organization and the information needed to make that
 organization function effectively.

 ::>Bargain

 The ability to manipulate the perceived value of one side of an
 exchange relative to the other, through non-coercive techniques.
 Could legitimately be a specific application of "Persuasion".

 ::>Broker

 The ability to act for another in trade.  Includes knowing what a
 fair price is, and being willing to buy and sell using your own
 funds at that fair price to close a transaction.  (i.e., if the
 fair price for the load of foodstuffs you brought in is 6000
 Cr/Tonne, but nobody is offering more than 5300, the broker should
 be able to buy from you at 5700, and hold on to it until the local
 price rises enough for him to sell at a profit.  Similarly, that
 same broker will stock up on merchandise when the price is low,
 and sell to you below the prevailing price, but still at a profit,
 if the prevailing price is unacceptably high.  In this way, he
 influences the market (smoothing out the long-term graph) in
 proportion to his holdings and capital.)

 ::>Steward (D) [where does this go? Professional Skills? Other Skills?]

 I see this as a "Professional" skill - it is the skills necessary
 for personal service (in the sense of servants in a filthy-rich
 person\'s mansion - butler, maid, bath girl/boy, hair stylist,
 manicurist, social calendar arranger, and so on).  It also
 encompasses certain aspects of Customer Service (i.e., handling
 multiple people, arranging personal services, dealing with
 complaints, etc.)

 ::>Trader

 Knowledge of what goods are generally available or generally in
 demand in which locations, and what quality of brokerage service
 is available.



 ::>***OTHER SKILLS**************************

 ::>Language (C)
 ::> -Choose a particular language

 ::>[Note:  I think language skills should be given as part of the
 ::>character\'s "background package" or some step which is not part of career
 ::>resolution. This resolves the problem of "wasting" skills on gaining
 ::>languages.  Having grown up in Quebec, I\'m bilingual, but not because of
 ::>any "training"]

 There\'s been some discussion of this.  Languages learned as you
 did should _not_ count against skills, but any learned after
 starting career resolution _should_ count against skills.  I also
 lean toward classification of language groups, with (say)
 Spanish-3 giving Portuguese-2 and Italian-0.5 and such.

 ::>Perception (D) [I don\'t like the idea of a seperate Observation skill.
 ::>The argument was good, and I too am a good observer but bad perceiver,
 ::>but I feel this dilutes things a bit too much]

 No, I buy the argument.  Perception is _not_ observation, and if
 you ever study police work from the inside, you\'ll see just how
 different they are.

 ::>Recon (D) [maybe we should call this skill scouting or something like that?]

 No, Reconnaissance is perfectly OK.

 ::>Survey [could someone please explain to me what this skill is?]

 The Orienteer or Navigator can find his way around.  The Scout
 (Recon Agent) can find out what\'s going on.  The Surveyor can tell
 either one the "lay" of the area, and generate a reasonably
