>  I have no idea of what an atlatl is, but Crossbow is probably more
>  akin to your Ranged Weapon than to the others listed here.  And
>  bow (as in conventional, not cross) is far different from sling.

An atlatl (aka woomera aka throwing stick) is a long stick with a
"hook" sticking out near the end. The "hook" fits into a notch on the
end of a spear. 

 /==================>    <-spear
/======================  <-atlatl

You grasp the end that\'s near the spear head and use it to throw the
spear. What it does is effectibely make your arm longer, thus *greatly*
increasing the lever arm. This makes the spear go faster and hit harder.
It makes a *big* difference and was invented independently at least 3
times.

Personally, I\'d go with a "thrown missile" skill that broke down into
chunks like this:

rock/grenade/etc
spear
  Atlatl
bow/crossbow
sling
  staff sling (a staff with a sling on the end)
special (boomerang, shuriken, knives, etc)

BTW slings and staff slings were used until fairly late in the middle
ages and *revived* for a while around WWI for throwing grenades
farther. The rifle grenade and RPG ended this. But it\'s still something
"hi tech" a character could do with a "lo tech" skill!

>  Toss this group, or convert it to Archaic Weapons (Group,
>  level-nil) and add cudgel/mace/axe/hammer, blade, and polearm.  If
>  you go with the latter, copy Crossbow into the Ranged Weapon
>  group.

Crossbows don\'t out range bows. They are just easier to use. 

>  I\'d make Hammer/Mace part of this cluster, possibly as additional
>  weapons in Long.  I\'m not sure where to put Axe.

hammer/mace do *not* work like cudgels, or staffs, due to the weight
being concentrated at the end. And it makes a difference wether it\'s a
one hand (short) weapon, a two hand (longer) or a pole arm (yes, they
mace pole arm maces!)

Axes probably go in a similar progression from one-hand thru poleaxe.
BTW, someone who can use an axe can use a mace at about the same skill
level. But going the other way doesn\'t work as well (it matters more
which way the axehead is oriented).

But for simplicity you could probably combine the axe/mace/hammer
sequences. 

(In case you hadn\'t guessed I\'m in the SCA :-)

