>Renaissance coming out of the Dark Ages.  If this is a valid model 
>(maybe it\'s not), then its doubtful Sylea is going to know much of 
>anything about a lot of worlds...even obsolete information, and the 
>pocket empires on the fringes are going to know even less.
>
>Thoughts?

        Absolutely.  The Sylean\'s knowledge of former Imperial Space, and
that\'s a lot of space, would be limited to what was known at the height of
the Second Imperium/Rule of Man, some Fifteen Centuries before hand.  Now
assuming that their original data bases have remained intact for 1500 years,
a fact which in the first place may well be something of a streatch there\'s
a awful lot that can happen in 1500 years, not to mention language drift,
culture change and warfare, lets face it the Vargr and Aslan weren\'t just
sitting around at this time looking across the borders thinking "Oh those
poor humans.  Let\'s give them a bit of a breather for now and turn our
attentions elsewhere."  Pardon me but if I was a Vargr captian or an Aslan
Iheati I think the first thing in my mind would be, "Power Vacuum and well
developed worlds ripe for the taking.  Yee Haww!  Saddle up the ponies tex
we\'re gonna have us a good time tonight."

        Returning to the areas that were Imperial at that time would be a
lot like returning to the Wilds in TNE.  No one knows just what the hell is
out there but expect wierdness and lots of it.  The only advantage the
Sylean\'s have over the RC is they didn\'t have their tecnoligical base
stripped completely away and they don\'t have to worry about Vampire Fleets.
Of course they do have to worry about canibalisic natives, pirates,
marauders, evil dictators, and some kind of odd wobbly thing that\'s made the
entire spinward marches disappear.

        Imagine the knowledge that\'s been lost.  Look at how much the
Greeks, Roman\'s and Egyptians knew three thousand years ago and compare it
to how much we didn\'t know one thousand years ago.  We lost a lot of
information in a very short time, and generally speaking we were just to
damn close minded for 500 years to even imaging that their might have been
other possiblities.  Of course when the church told you, you were going to
hell if you though up something new it kind of put the kibosh on any great
thinking.  "Go to hell -- remain ignorant -- go to hell . . . I think I\'ll
remain ignorant."

        Though few people are going to admit it T4 is just TNE set in an era
where the collapse hasn\'t been as all encompassing and total.  I think I
might like this after all.  "High didalee dee a pirates life for me."  My
question is how will tasks be resolved?

Derek Stanley

