> Religious Scholar Example:

This is a really good example.  I never worried about NPCs that might 
logically come out of the character generation process until I started 
playing the Hero system, with its emphasis on dependant NPCs, Hunteds, 
etc.  After that, it just made sense to include them in Traveller as 
well. I\'m glad I\'m not the only one!

BTW, this would be a great addition to the Merchant Captain Alexander 
Jamison character creation example (or whatever is included in T4): 
noting where a referee might, if s/he chooses, logically infer NPCs that 
should be generated based on the events in the character generation 
process.  I think it would give beginning referees a great opportunity to 
help players create more life-like characters, and imbue the 
campaign-universe with more realism as well.  When the campaign starts, 
the characters would not just be experienced - they would have at least a 
minor group of friends, enemies, and contacts.  A frame of reference in 
the social order, if you will.

> IMO details and background are what make for an interesting charator, not
> pages of little used (or understood) skills!  

I agree.  While a humongous list of skills makes for a more realistic 
system, there is a point at which additional skills confer little or no 
benefit to the majority of players.  The little black books had too few 
skills, certainly.  But CT as a whole had just about the right amount of 
skills.  

I added a few in my campaigns, but I think that is something each referee 
should be prepared to do as needed.  I see little benefit in IG providing 
referees with an exhaustive skill list, since that means many of those 
skills will never be used by most referees.

Each basic character type should have skills avaiable to him or her which 
provide the /majority/ of skills a character in that profession would 
logically have.  Yes, I believe it is unnecessary to provide for every 
skill every character type could ever possibly use.  There are so very 
many fields of study open to a Scholar character that deliniating them 
all would be preposterous - the list would probably be equal in number to 
all other skills in the system.  And, again, most of those skills would 
go unused in most campaigns.

I remember when AD&D started using the Proficiency and Specialization 
systems.  It added a lot of detail to the game, but it was (IMO) at the 
expense of playability.  In AD&D\'s case, that was just one more step down 
the road of complexity - and it was already well down that road.  I\'d 
really rather not see Traveller follow suit.

The CT system, at the time of the introduction of The Traveller Book, had 
the best approach as far as complexity is concerned.  The Book had 
everything needed in order to play the game - and all systems were quick 
and simple - very playable, and realistic enough.  If a group wanted to 
introduce more complexity and realism into the game, they could buy Books 
4-8, the Supplements, and/or various other expansion modules by GDW and 
the licensees.  

Complexity was completely optional, and the Traveller Book was a 
self-contained role-playing game (that is, there were no systems missing, 
although each system favored playability over realism).  Perfect.

The list of skills that Marc Miller recently posted appeared, to me, to 
provide plenty of skills for the basic book.  As necessary, when 
supplementary material comes out that requires new skills (ie, if a 
Citizens of the Imperium II or whatever comes out), it would make sense 
to expand the skill list.  Beyond that, I see little use for an attempt 
to make the skill system perfectly complete.

Comments welcome!


