> Thanks Derek, for correcting the first posting.  As an archaeological
> graduate, and in terms of Traveller, I\'d have to argue that one of the
> Imperium\'s primary archaeological fields would be "Ancients Studies", and
> of course for that you\'d have no written history to go on.  I\'d suggest
> that advanced "non-destructive site recording" and "artifact
> interpretation" would be at the top of the 56th Century\'s archaeological
> skills.  Certainly for my own degree, only a third or so was spent on
> history (mainly Roman), the rest of the course was primarily concerned with
> the techniques and development of archaeological excavation and the
> preservation and social interpretation of finds.  Never hot wired any cars
> though...    ...is it the same as doing it to an air-raft?

Lets face it.  Studying the ancients in Trav would be like studying the Romans or 
Mayans or Egypians in our century.  It\'s the big stuff that everyone wants to get 
involved in.  However, there\'s a certian dark side to this work.  Because of the 
importance of Ancients sites, at TL21+ there\'s a lot of really important gear lying 
around on these sites, you\'d end up with a political officer and a troop of 
soliders every time you tried to dig up something.  Kinda like working in Mexico or 
Peru.  THe sites would all be mapped insitu with out having to disturb anything, 
just imaging what ground penetrating sensors are like then, wow!  Unfortunately 
in order to recover and study the artifacts you\'d still need to get on your hands 
and knees and dig the place up.  Or in the case of some work I\'ve seen out here 
wait for the D9 to tear the place appart and pick up what\'s left.  Youch that\'s a 
nasty way to work.

Working in europe I wouldn\'t imagine there\'s much call for hot wiring.  You\'re 
never extremely far away from something or some one.  Here in Canada when someone 
loses the keys and the nearest town is 150 miles away someone had better be a 
professional break in artist.  I wonder if air rafts are easy to hot wire...  and I 
wonder if they\'re still using 10cm mason pointing trowels in T4.  We got pretty 
good at throwing those things after two months in the field.

Derek Stanley
