The skill numbers should not define the character. His role playing
should define the character. Subtle guidance from the GM will ensure
this. (Some times not so subtle :)

My players, and I when playing, have defined the context that the
skills were acquired in. I have a Barbarian TNE character that has
enforced an Intelligence check on himself every time he is faced with
technology. No prodding from me (the GM). This Barbarian has acquired a
Small Arms skill from another player character who was a Special Forces
Instructor. However, that does not mean that any weapon he picks up, he
knows how to operate. He enforces the unfamiliarity because, he doesn\'t
have the Tech-Level background to figure out that it is the same as the
one the Instructor showed him. In fact, whenever there are new weapons
to be used, the Instructor now takes the time to show him how to use
the weapon. 

IMO the characters *must* use the skills in context to define their
persona. GM\'s *must* enforce that context! The skills issue is moot.
Too many skills only slows down the CharGen process, and that can be
remedied, since the GM should be taking interest in the PC\'s
development anyway. (To gain contextual information!)

