There are two "Quick and Easy Systems", actually.  One, The Quick Ship
Design System (QSD System) is on the same complexity level as Book 2, and
was done by me.  You literally select from tables and add up columns - the
intent was that you could reasonably design a ship with nothing more than
the rulebook and a pencil and paper (there\'s only two places where you have
to divide, and only six multiplications in the whole sequence, so the
calculator is optional).  It\'s truly "plug-and-chug".

The result is (within a fairly limited scope: 100 to 5000 ton ships, and a
reasonable but small set of hull, weapon and sensor options) a ship rated
for the MMT starship combat system, that is also a valid FF&S design.

I\'ll see if I can get permission to make the design system available on the
\'net somewhere.  I believe the QSD System will be included in the basic MMT
rulebooks, so that you\'ll be able to design and customize ships immediately.

The second system is FF&S "Lite", being put together by David Golden.  He\'s
got the current mock-up on his web site.  FF&S "Lite" is a bit more complex;
you\'ll need a calculator work out your design.  On the other hand, it\'s a
LOT more flexable, is still much easier than FF&S, and also produces MMT
statistics and valid FF&S designs.  FF&S "Lite" will probably be included
with the starship book product.

Since both systems are based on FF&S, you can mix and match steps: if you
don\'t like any of the QSD System\'s available hulls, you can generate a hull
with FF&S Lite, and then fill it with QSD System components and have a valid
design.  You can use FF&S to design a new weapons system, and then "package"
it up for use with QSD System or FF&S Lite.

I think we\'ve really got the best of both (all three?) worlds with MMT.

Guy Garnett, aka
