    'from' => 'Dhivael',
    'body' => '>However, at no point along its length is the cable (which has mass, probably
>a lot of mass) in orbit.  For example, a section of cable 200km above the
>earth\'s surface travels "around" the planet in 24h and is thus moving at a
>very much lower velocity than a satellite orbiting at the same altitude.
>The cable is therefore not "weightless", and exerts a downwards force on the
>orbiting anchor.

The cable\'s _radial_ velocity is the same as that of the satellite - it
completes 2*pi radians in 24 hours. It\'s just the same as the rotation of the
planet - a point on the surface of the planet and a point somewhere inside
the planet are moving at different speeds, but their angular velocity is
the same,
otherwise the planet would break up.

>Is it not then the case that no matter how massive the anchor the cable
>would eventually drag it down to the planetary surface, with catastrophic
>consequences?

I think that the most likely candidate for drag is going to be the effect
of the planet\'s atmosphere on the cable, but I don\'t have any figures for
that, I\'m afraid.

Nik.

