    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ad940',
    'body' => 'On Tue, 11 Jun 1996, John R. Snead wrote:

> The only problem is that any religious scholar should have History skill
> too. My problem with CT was that it had just about the right number of
> *military* skills.  You can\'t play a decent scientist or scholar in that
> system (I\'ve tried, having never had any interest in playing a military
> character).  T4 doesn\'t need many more skills and IMHO *shouldn\'t* have
> many more skills than CT, but it needs a greater diversity of skills. The
> MT skill list was a little long, but had just the right amount of
> diversity. 

I agree with you that Traveller needs more non-military characters than 
the basic CT system had.  This means it needs more skills to support 
those characters.  But which skills?  

For instance, I don\'t remember the character list Marc posted having a 
Religious Scholar.  It had a Scholar, but it wasn\'t specialized.  But, 
hey, you\'ve gotta have /some/ skills for specialization, right?  Right.

But, again, which ones?  If we choose to include every single discipline, 
we\'re going to have a humongous list of skills (many of which won\'t be 
used in most campaigns).  Does it make more sense to make some broad 
choices that are not too specific (ie, top-level skills rather than 
breaking them down into their component skills - Computer Science, 
rather than Database Systems, Management Information Systems, and 
Programming - let alone a further breakdown (for instance of Programming 
into each computer langauge, or of any computer skill into 
platform-specific skills)), or to allow for the widely applicable, 
low-level skills such as languages, computer use, etc.?

With only a very few additions, the complete CT list of skills can serve 
to allow for any area of study, as Daniel\'s Theology example shows.  This 
method appears to be the best way to go.

- -Joe  
