ELSE OUT THERE!

The RPG systems on the market in 1977 were D&D, Tunnels & Trolls, and 
a few other Fantasy RPG\'s.  It was the first SF RPG, and therefore 
was successful, almost by default.  It was an elegant system for the 
time, but lets face it, a lot of CT looks like a greybeard at this 
point in terms of rule system.  This is the reason for a task system, better, more 
comprehensive ship and craft design.  Look at the number of early 
Traveller licensees who now make products that compete within the same niche:  
Games Workshop (Adventure 4: Leviathan), FASA (Sky Raiders, and a ton of 
other stuff), DGP (Soon to come out with AI, they basically designed 
MegaTraveller).  

Hell, I bought my second set of Little Black Books at Waldenbooks for 
heavens sake.  Those days are gone.  They will NEVER be back.  The 
market has matured, there are other SF RPG\'s out there, and in the case 
of the SF market, games with very recognizable licensing (Star Wars, 
Star Trek), are directly competing.    Plus, the RPG market has shrunk 
compared to those days.  I live across the way from a guy who bought 
the CT boxed set, and never used them.  At that time, people bought 
RPG\'s they never used, kind of like people buy CCG\'s today.  
GDW, TSR and others got rich then in a way that the companies 
around now would have a hard time doing.  A lot of people got into 
RPG\'s for a couple years in the late 70\'s and early 80\'s, and then got out.  
Then about 83-85, a lot of the early companies fell like leaves from the 
trees in autumn, as a lot of players moved on.  Frankly, I was that way 
for a while.  I didn\'t get back into it until about 1990 after having not 
played a game since 1984.

If you think that just reissuing the little black books in a single 
bound volume is going to allow IG to take shelf space away from West 
End Games (Star Wars), & FASA (Starfleet Battles), you are deluding 
yourself.  Very few people would give a system that relied solely on something 
as crude as Book 2, Starships for ship design a 2nd glance today, not 
even me.

Stu
 
