    'index' => 'ad968',
    'body' => 'Hi there

If you take a line with a mass at each end, reeled in intially so that
the masses are next to each other and so in the same orbit, and then
you reel the line out so that one mass heads planetwards and the other
spacewards, the result is something which orbits at the rate of the
centre of the line.  This is difficult to do, as the Space Shuttle
tether experiments show.  A beanstalk would be the extreme case; much
smaller lines entirely in space could conceivably be used to generate
power, sling loads into deep space, or decellerate incoming
spaceships.  To make the beanstalk (a la Red Mars), you put a
planetoid in geostationary orbit above where you want the thing to
come down, and then reel a line out in both directions.  The lines act
as counterweights.  However, if you make the spaceward line denser, or
thicker, or whatever, it doesn\'t need to go as far out as the
planetward one needs to go down.

BTW in Red Mars, the beanstalk was broken at the geostationary
planetoid: It then fell in a spectacular fashion, wrapping itself
twice around the planet, and causing a lot of damage (a great passage
in the book).  The planetoid whizzed off to Jupiter, or something like
that.  If you broke a beanstalk at the base, the whole things would
whizz out into space, although there would probably be a hell of a
sonic boom as the tail end was pulled through the atmosphere.
Tactically, I suspect the Red Mars rebels would have done a better job
if they had wiped out the anchor on the planet, so that there wouldn\'t
have been the massive collateral damage, but it wouldn\'t have been
such a vivid read!

There is a Traveller adventure called Tower Trouble in an old White
Dwarf, which details what is essentially a "great train robbery in the
sky", and is set on a beanstalk rising from Ecuador on Terra.  I think
the main reason beanstalks aren\'t prevelant in Traveller is that grav
travel is so much easier and safer; an elevator only makes sense when
the competition are using rockets.  I think the Terra Tower in the WD
adventure suggested that it was built before gravitics came of age on
Terra (about 2020 AD?), although that would make it 3000 years old!

Stewart Eyres <spe@astro.keele.ac.uk>
