    'topic' => 'Beanstalks',
    'body' => 'Jamie Young wrote:
>>  For example, a section of cable 200km above the earth\'s surface travels
"around" the planet in 24h and is thus moving at a
very much lower velocity than a satellite orbiting at the same 
altitude.The cable is therefore not "weightless", and exerts a 
downwards force on the orbiting anchor.

Is it not then the case that no matter how massive the anchor 
the cable would eventually drag it down to the planetary surface, with
catastrophic consequences? <<

If you set it up that way then yes, you\'re heading for trouble. But
at the same time you send a cable down the well you move the rock up above it\'s
original position as a balance (conservation of angular momentum). 1 point on
the cable is in orbit, but the rock is above 
that, tugging outwards by the same degree the cable below tugs inwards - the
entire system is orbiting about it\'s centre of mass, and there is no force up or
down. There will be a lot of tension in the cable, due to the difference in
gravity between the two endpoints, which is why it can\'t be done with current
materials.

                            David

