    'index' => 'ae003',
    'body' => 'On 06/13/96 at 10:22 AM,  Jamie Young <jamie@tsc.scotnet.co.uk> said:

>I\'m not sure about the idea of a counterweight: I don\'t think it
>would work either (I\'m so down on everything today :-)). 

Yeah, that would probably work just fine.  Quite a few folks
(scientist/engineer types) have looked at the concept in the past and
it\'s well grounded <pun intended>.  The problem is the cable has to be
made of unobtainum!  <g> The tensile strength of diamond fiber would
do it, but it\'ll be a while before we have that much diamond fiber
cable.  A beanstalk on the moon would be doable with current
technology..maybe Mars too, not *sure* about that.

>In Scotland we have a third verdict in court: "Not Proven".  This is
>how I feel about Space Elevators. 

Sure, *nothing* is really proven until somebody does it. <g>

Here are some more ideas I\'ve run across over the last 25 years..all
very possible, all very unlikely to ever be built. The people
describing them were engineering types, and the science behind them
seemed sound.  If nothing else they\'re ideas we can incorporate into
games to give them some flavor. [Source Analog magazine]

1.  Space Fountain - Your elevator cable is composed of a framework of
semi-circular magnets (think mass driver).  Fire iron slugs up the
driver and back down to the ground.  The slugs provide support for the
framework.  Once you start, keep adding sections to the framework
driving the slugs higher and higher until you have reached a hundred
miles or so.  Attach a car to the framework and ride it to orbital
altitude. Supposedly, if this thing collapsed it would fall straight
down and not spread out.  Supposedly it would work.  (I\'ve got doubts
about this one, but I seem to recall Dr Robert Forward writing about
it.  <G>)

2.  Space Loop - Link lightweight magnetic strips into a loop a couple
of hundred miles long.  Put several strong magnetic drivers along the
strip and start accelerating the links.  As the links accelerate along
the ground centriphical force causes the top half of the loop to
elevate.  At some speed the top of the loop is above the atmosphere. 
Link in slightly more massive links as the whole thing is spinning for
increased support.  Now construct a *lightweight* framework around the
loop, and you can send a tram around to the top and back down on the
framework. You could also drop an elevator cable down from the top. 
Believe it or not, the science behind this one looks solid.  Dangerous
as ##$@!  Probably expensive as that too..but most likely doable. The
suggestion was to do this at sea down along the equator for safety
sake.  This macro-lariat idea came from some folks down at Texas A&M.

3.  The Walking Stick (Or as I call it "The Hook") - Don\'t build a
beanstalk down to the surface, instead put a relatively small station
in low earth orbit.  Extend a cable from the station from either side
and rotate the station against the direction of orbit.  The cable will
approach the ground such that the relative velocity between the cable
and the surface is only a few hundred (or few thousand) miles an hour. 
Now a sub-orbital spaceplane flys up and matches speed with the cable
(remember the cable is overtaking the earth\'s rotation), and links a
cargo pod onto the cable.  The pod rides the cable up into space as
the station pulls in both cables.  The station loses momentum, giving
it to the pod, so the station has to boost now and then to stay in
orbit, but it\'s cheaper to boost *from* orbit than to boost all the
way too orbit.  This idea is a small part of the tests the Shuttle\'s
been doing with that long cable they\'ve been extending out the bay. 
The other part of the idea is to generate electricity from that cable
extending through the earth\'s magnetic field...the station steals
momentum from the earth using the earth\'s momentum to help it maintain
orbit.  The cable doesn\'t have to actually enter the atmosphere, or be
all that long.  This one could really work, and wouldn\'t cost an arm
and leg to test out.

4.  The Space Ring - Now this one is *far* out!  Build a linked ring
around the earth in orbit.  Suborbital spaceplane flys up achieving
the altitude but not orbital speed.  Figuratively *lands* on the
ring..actually links on and uses the ring\'s momentum to pull up to
orbital velocity.  The ring maintains it\'s orbit stealing from the
earth\'s momentum.  The fly in the ointment is getting the ring in
place in the first place, and it has to be a complete ring for
structural stability.

I honestly *love* ideas like this! <g>

Eris
