    'body' => 'Another way of anchoring a beanstalk is to build an orbiting torrid, and
lower 2-6 beanstalks at equidistant points around the torrid. This idea is
stolen from "A Tour of the Galaxy", where earth\'s "Elevators" are raised
from equitorial meso-america and africa, and (I assume) asia. The cables
were lowered from the skeletal torrid, and once the elevators were in, they
were used to send up more goodies (ones that couldn\'t survive cannon
launch).

Expensive, but also allows for nearly a billion persons in comfort in the
ring/torrid/satelite.

Since the cables are dropped from equidistant points, their net surfaceward
forces would roughly cancel out, leaving a situation where you simply need
to strengthen the ring. (BTW, the ring is not in in geosynch. After
construction, one use thrusters were used to slow it so that the cables
could be dropped.)

