    'index' => 'ae130',
    'body' => 'At 01:41 PM 6/17/96 -0600, you wrote:

>I can gloss the system too, but I *hate* doing it.  In fact, heritic
>that I am, I don\'t really like the idea of "the main world."  <g> In
>many systems there are several settlements scattered across several
>worlds.  The players might have business at any of them.  

If only there was a computer program that would do this and not create ten
thousand pages of tables.  Something that details a system like we would
detail a system.

>I set up lots systems where the "Port of Entry" is a good starport on
>a small airless rock with only a few hundred people employed
>there...often a moon or an asteriod.  Cargos and passengers incoming
>or outgoing to other systems funnel through there.  

This is a cool idea.  Like Gateway Station.  I never though of it for Trav
though.  If you look at a Starwars Module "Platts guide to Starports" there
are some very cool ideas and sketches in there.

>Sometimes they aren\'t even allowed to take their ships to other
>locations in the system..for various reasons.  Maybe the local
>government wants to control imports/exports (tarrifs, religious
>reasons, etc).  Other times it\'s said to be a "safety" measure, for
>whatever reason.  Often the real reason is to force ships to buy fuel
>at the offical gaspumps. <G>

I hate buying fuel from the locals.  I\'ll go out of my way to get it free.
I\'ve got a system where it\'s illegal to use active sensors on the main
planet.  Why?  The locals are hiding something?  The Ancients have set up a
taco stand?  Who knows but when you give players these kinds of regulations
they go nuts.  Well I know, but that\'s none of their buisness.

>The main population centers are elsewhere in the system.  So are some
>of the adventures.  <g>
>
>I *do* agree with you about maps.  I really like maps too! ;)

Maps are the best thing a GM has for story telling, prop wise that is.

DS

