    'body' => 'On 06/18/96 at 10:56 PM,  derek stanley <dstanley@direct.ca> said:

>This is true, unfortunately lets face it the average stutterwarp ship
> could run rings about a HEPLAR ship, not to sure about grav plates
>but  introducing something like this totally changes the face of
>space.  You  can do it just be very careful about the type of travel
>you wish to  offer.

Right!  The GM has to live with the consequences of her
decisions.  <g> 

If you put stutterwarp in a game as one technology and have other
ships maneuvering with reaction drives then you\'ve got a potential
problem in game balance.  But there are things you can do...

Maybe stutterwarp can\'t get above 3xftp (400 days to travel 1 parsec),
so it\'s not as efficient or economical as regular jump drives, but
it\'s hell on wheels in-system.  Would Stutter be used as the FTL drive
on most ships?  Not if they could get jump, but it would be a good
backup and maybe an excellent Mdrive.

As far as in-system travel is concerned...well, stutterwarp isn\'t
normally FTL in-system and could have several potential problems of
their own:  1. doesn\'t work near a strong grav well, so you can\'t
land/launch with one; 2. doesn\'t give you *real* velocity, so just
*how* is a stutter going to match orbital velocities once it gets to a
planet (???), if it stutters up to the planet and turns off the drive
the ship\'s actual momentum probably won\'t match the planet\'s; 3.
standard stutters can maneuver like a banshee, but you don\'t have to
play them that way, there are very legitimate ways to limit their
ability to instantly start/stop and change direction.

BTW, I was thinking about (2) yesterday.  Stutter a ship in front of a
planet travelling in orbit at 30kps and turn off the drive. What\'s the
ship\'s momentum in its current frame of reference? Could be
anything..depends on what it was when it turned the stutter
on...right?  So, let\'s say for this example that when it entered the
system it had 0 momentum with regard to the star. Now you have a 30kps
KE bomb sitting in front of the planet!

So much for stutterwarps (or any reactionless drive) eliminating the
planet killer.  If there is a way to put a ship/object in the path of
a planet then the planet can provide all the KE you need for a big
bang.  Well, I guess you could get around even this, but it *is* an
added complication.

Eris
